 exist. <br>  <br> 4.) My consensus is the type of player that would buy it is one that doesn't really know what he/she is getting into. <br>  <br> 5.) Most people that have bought characters are just n00bs to me. <br>  <br> 6 and 7.) No because you don't know if the character you bought was a trainer, griefer, scam artist, idiot, or general problem child. When you buy a character, you tend to buy the reputation also. I consider it not worth the risk at all. I'm willing to guess at least 30-40% of anyone who sells an account is doing it because they screwed up their rep, and want to use it to make some cash on the side, and then start over. Also I know a few examples of characters bought on a server have turned out to be banned by the time they changed hands. ALSO, if the person retains the original CD-keys, they could call up SoE, and go, &quot;My account was hacked and the password was changed! Here is the CD-key registered to the account!&quot; And they will get the character back. <br>  <br>  <br> My suggestion if you have a high level character is to buy another account and PL the character you want to have. Failing that, find some friends to play. I had friends that got to level 47 in 2-3 months when they started together. They loved to explore and exp'ed everywhere instead of bothering with easyloop(tm). <br>  <br> Buying accounts is just not a risk worth taking, imo. <br>  <br>  <br>  <br>  <br>  <br>  <br> <p></p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span><div class="SignatureText">Common sense isn't common. <br> Shivering: Failing daily for the VS Emerald. <br> Representing the EQ ranger fetal position since 1999 <br> EQ2 - The next generation of the Silvershard wood elf ranger clan. <br> Rangers all the way! Hoorah! <br> </div></td></tr><tr align="right" valign="bottom"><td colspan=2 class="BoardRowB"><a class="BoardRowBLink" href="/help/default.asp?goto=faqs%2Easp%23lockedtopic">Locked Topic</a> | <a href="/active_topic